[[File:Patrick Anthony Ludden.jpg|thumb|Patrick Anthony Ludden]]
'''Patrick Anthony Ludden''' (February 4, 1836 &ndash; August 6, 1912) was an [[Ireland|Irish]]-born [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He was the first [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse, New York]] (1887<U+2013>1912).

==Biography==
Patrick Ludden was born in [[Breaffy]], near [[Castlebar]], [[County Mayo]], to Anthony and Ellen (n<U+00E9>e Fitzgerald) Ludden.<ref name=diocese>{{cite news|work=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse]]|title=Most Rev. Patrick Anthony Ludden|url=http://www.syrdio.org/bishop.asp?path=Bishop&action=viewBishop&BishopID=10}}</ref> He graduated from [[St. Jarlath's College]] in [[Tuam]] in 1861 and then immigrated to [[North America]], where he entered the [[Grand s<U+00E9>minaire de Montr<U+00E9>al|Grand Seminary of Montreal]] in [[Quebec]], [[Canada]].<ref name=USCHA>{{cite book|title=Historical Records and Studies|publisher=United States Catholic Historical Society}}</ref> After completing his [[Theology|theological]] studies, he was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priesthood]] by Bishop [[Ignace Bourget]] on May 21, 1864.<ref name=hierarchy>{{cite news|work=Catholic-Hierarchy.org|title=Bishop Patrick Anthony Ludden|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bludden.html}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2015}}</ref> He was attached to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Albany|Diocese of Albany]] in [[New York]], and there served as [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] of St. Joseph's Church in [[Malone (village), New York|Malone]].<ref name=diocese/> He was shortly afterwards named [[Chancellor (ecclesiastical)|chancellor]] of the diocese, and accompanied Bishop [[John J. Conroy]] as his theologian to the [[First Vatican Council]].<ref name=diocese/> In 1872 he became rector of the [[Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception (Albany, New York)|Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception]] and [[vicar general]] of the diocese.<ref name=USCHA/> He was named rector of St. Peter's Church in [[Troy, New York|Troy]] in 1880.<ref name=catholic>{{cite news|work=[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]|title=Syracuse|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/14397a.htm}}</ref>

On December 14, 1886, Ludden was appointed the first [[Ordinary (officer)|Bishop]] of the newly erected [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Diocese of Syracuse]] by [[Pope Leo XIII]].<ref name=hierarchy/> He received his [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|episcopal]] [[consecration]] on May 1, 1887 from Archbishop [[Michael Corrigan]], with Bishops [[Bernard John McQuaid]] and [[Francis McNeirny]] serving as [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]].<ref name=hierarchy/> During his 25-year-long tenure, he presided over a period of great growth in the young diocese.

At the time of Ludden's arrival, the diocese contained 70,000 Catholics, 74 priests, 46 [[Parish (Catholic Church)|parishes]], 20 [[Mission (Christian)|mission]] churches, and 16 [[parochial school]]s.<ref name=USCHA/><ref name=catholic/> By the time of his death, there were over 150,000 Catholics, 129 priests, 80 parishes, 36 mission churches, and 21 parochial schools.<ref name=USCHA/> He selected [[Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception (Syracuse, New York)|St. Mary's Church]] as his new [[cathedral]] in 1903, and dedicated it in September 1910.<ref name=catholic/> In 1911 he gained a degree of notoriety when he declared that the deadlock in the [[New York Legislature]] over the election of [[William F. Sheehan]] to the [[United States Senate]] was due to [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|anti-Catholicism]]. Sheehan was later defeated.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|date=1912-08-07|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Bishop Ludden Dead at 76}}</ref>

Bishop Ludden died at his residence in [[Syracuse, New York]], aged 74. He is buried in the [[crypt]] of the Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception in Syracuse.<ref name=diocese/> [[Bishop Ludden Junior/Senior High School]] is named after him.

